<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor=""  width="95%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post120778"></a>
	
	<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Shadowfrost</b></font><br>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">did Ragefire the hard way</font><br>
	<p>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Registered: Jun 2002<br>
	Location: <br>
	Posts: 503</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"> <b></b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Things I don't want</b><br />
<br />
Further undead-specific powers are meaningless in the context of current game content.  In other words, there is <b>no point whatsoever</b> in increased anti-undead powers when there's such a dearth of actual undead monsters to use them on !  Furthermore, necromancers and paladins do not need clerics stepping further into their territory.<br />
<br />
Further improvements to healing will not help clerics in xp groups.  In other words, when your group can chain-pull with no downtime, your group has enough healing and doesn't need any more.  The only way that a cleric will provide added value to a group which matches that provided by a shaman or druid, is if the cleric provides damage output.<br />
<br />
<b>Things I do want</b><br />
<br />
a) Meaningful plate armour.  At the moment the cleric class has the graphic and the encumbrance associated with plate armour but we lack the defensive skills to make it meaningful.  Surely common sense says that cleric defensive skills should be similar to those possessed by bards.<br />
<br />
b) Since clerics now melee, it's ridiculous not to bring our weapon skill caps in line with those of shamans.  However, that's not really a balance issue since even a 200 cap wouldn't make much difference to our damage output; it's just a niggle.<br />
<br />
c) Reasonable scaling to our spells.  We have one version of Unswerving Hammer of Faith when this should be a spell line which scales up and down the levels.  We have one version of MoR, one new version coming in PoP, and one clickie from a VT item, when again this should be a spell line which scales up and down the levels.  Mark of Karn has one live version and one which may come in PoP, and again does not really scale.<br />
<br />
d) Expansion of the Mark of Retribution/Mark of Karn line, particularly a Mark of Mana line which resembles Mark of Karn but gives a mana boost when the mob is hit rather than a hp boost.  These Marks are unique to clerics, so expanding upon them does not tread on the toes of any other class, and also they do not stack, so they will have far more impact on the XP group game where clerics actually need help, than on the raiding game where we do not.  They also offer many opportunities to buff the cleric class in a creative way rather than to blur the lines between the priest casters even more.<br />
<br />
e) Ensnare.  Since so many other classes can already affect the mob's movement speed, and since one race of clerics (dark elf) already has access to a clickie Clinging Darkness item, while all the others can obtain charged clickie or proccing snare items with relative ease, this isn't so much a class balance issue as a matter of basic convenience.<br />
<br />
f) Self-invis.  See `Ensnare.`<br />
<br />
g) Group versions of our resist buffs with a reasonable duration, for goodness' sake.   It's nonsensical to continually have to remem a low-mana, short duration spell to rebuff an entire group !  The spells don't have to be any more powerful than they already are, just more user-friendly.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">__________________<br>
Shadowfrost</font></p></p>
	<p></p>
